          "body": "The chapter's briefest and most consequential sentence is 14:11a: 'But Amaziah would not listen.' Five words that summarize the mechanism of self-destruction. Jehoash had offered Amaziah a way out — 'enjoy your glory and stay at home' (14:10) — that preserved his dignity and Israel's peace. Amaziah refused. The battle at Beth-shemesh is presented without dramatization: Judah was defeated, they fled, Amaziah was captured, Jerusalem's wall was breached for 400 cubits, and the Temple treasury was stripped (14:11-14). The narrator wastes no sympathy on the outcome because Amaziah had been warned in precise terms about exactly this sequence ('you would fall, and Judah with you,' 14:10). The plundering of the Temple — gold, silver, articles, hostages — is particularly pointed. The king whose pride cost him the war also cost YHWH's house its treasures. Pride is never merely personal; it deplenishes what belongs to God and to others."
