          "title": "Jeroboam II: evil king, YHWH's instrument",
          "body": "The chapter's second half introduces Jeroboam II with an unambiguous negative evaluation (14:24) and then proceeds to narrate the most extensive territorial restoration in Israel's history since the Solomonic era (14:25). The tension is not accidental — the narrator is making a theological argument. YHWH's decision to save Israel through Jeroboam is grounded in two things: a prior prophetic word (through Jonah son of Amittai, 14:25) and YHWH's own compassion for an afflicted people with no human helper (14:26). The passage echoes the Exodus motif deliberately: Israel's affliction was 'very bitter' (marah), with 'neither bond nor free, nor any helper' — language that recalls the helplessness of Egyptian bondage before YHWH acted. As Douglas Moo and Peter Davids note in parallel contexts, the New Testament consistently grounds the same logic in Paul: God's gifts and calling are irrevocable (Romans 11:29), and his mercy operates independently of human worthiness. The Jeroboam II pericope is the Old Testament's clearest narrative illustration of that principle."
