          "body": "The chapter closes with two succession notices that form a theological diptych. Amaziah, who initiated a war he was warned not to fight, was assassinated by conspirators, fled to Lachish, was killed there, and was brought back on horseback for burial in Jerusalem (14:19-20). The people of Judah then took Azariah (later called Uzziah) and made him king at sixteen (14:21). Jeroboam II, the wicked instrument of YHWH's grace, 'slept with his fathers' after a forty-one year reign and was succeeded by Zechariah (14:29). The contrast in the manner of death is itself evaluative: Amaziah dies hunted and fleeing; Jeroboam II dies in his bed after the longest reign of any northern king since the dynasty's founding. The narrator does not comment on the irony, but the exilic reader feels it. YHWH's history is not a merit system. Pride reduces the partially-obedient; compassion exalts even the faithless when the covenant name of Israel is at stake. Both truths are necessary; neither cancels the other."
