        "number": 3,
        "title": "Beth-shemesh to Jerusalem — the cost of ignored warning",
        "range": "14:11-20",
        "excerpt": "Judah was defeated by Israel, and they fled each to his tent. Then Jehoash king of Israel captured Amaziah king of Judah... and came to Jerusalem and tore down the wall of Jerusalem.",
        "body": "The battle narrative (14:11-14) is compressed and unsentimental. The narrator records the defeat of Judah, the capture of Amaziah, the breach of Jerusalem's wall, the plunder of Temple and royal treasury, and the taking of hostages — all in four verses. The compression is itself a rhetorical judgment: there is nothing heroic here to narrate at length. Amaziah had been warned of precisely this outcome ('you would fall, and Judah with you,' 14:10); it occurred exactly as predicted.\n\nThe plundering of the Temple (14:14) carries special theological weight in Kings. The Temple treasury functions in the narrative as a barometer of covenant faithfulness — it is filled when the nation is faithful and depleted when it is not. Amaziah's war of pride has not merely cost him a battle; it has cost YHWH's house its sacred vessels and its gold. The king's personal ambition impoverishes the worship of God. This is one of the recurring patterns in the Kings narrative: royal sin has liturgical consequences, and the faithful remnant who worship at the Temple suffer the effects of a king's faithlessness.\n\nAmaziah survived his defeat and his humiliation by fifteen years (14:17) — a detail that intensifies rather than relieves the tragedy. He outlived Jehoash of Israel, who died in his bed (14:16), but spent those fifteen years as a king whose capital had been breached and whose treasury had been stripped. The conspiracy that eventually killed him (14:19) is the narrative's natural endpoint: a king who could not hold his border eventually could not hold his own city. The flight to Lachish and the assassination there follow the same pattern as his great-grandfather Joash (2 Kings 12:20) — conspiracy, flight, murder. The dynasty's recurring sin of pride generates a recurring pattern of violent ends.\n\nThe burial notice (14:20) — 'he was buried at Jerusalem with his fathers in the city of David' — grants Amaziah the dignity of a Davidic burial even in humiliation. The city of David does not reject its kings even when it conspires against them. The people's immediate installation of the sixteen-year-old Azariah (14:21) suggests that the conspiracy was not anarchic but orderly — Judah knew who the next king would be and moved quickly to establish continuity.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Parats* (broke down, v. 13) is a violent verb — to break through, breach, burst. It appears in contexts of boundary violation (Genesis 38:29; Exodus 19:22). *Otsar* (treasury, v. 14) is the storehouse for both Temple and royal valuables — its plundering signals the transfer of sacral wealth to a pagan capital. *Qesher* (conspiracy, v. 19) is the same word used of the plot against Joash in 12:20."
